**Lieutenant-General Sir William Erskine, 1st Baronet**

[Lieutenant-General](/Lieutenant_general_(United_Kingdom)) Sir William Erskine, 1st [Bt](/Baronet), an individual whose career spanned an impressive half-century within the [British Army](/British_Army), navigated the tumultuous landscapes of the mid-to-late 18th century. Born in 1719 in England, Erskine's life concluded on 19 March 1795, at the advanced age of 75 or 76, a testament to his endurance in an era defined by relentless conflict. His allegiance remained steadfastly with [Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain), serving from 1742 until his death, a tenure marked by consistent ascent through the ranks.

An engraving of Erskine, based on a portrait by [Richard Cosway](/Richard_Cosway), captures a glimpse of a man who commanded respect, though perhaps not warmth. Known informally by the rather uninspired nickname "Woolly," a moniker one imagines he endured rather than embraced, Erskine held the rank of [Lieutenant-General](/Lieutenant-general_(United_Kingdom)) by the close of his service. His commands were varied and significant, encompassing the swift [15th Light Dragoons](/15th_The_King%27s_Hussars), the steadfast [71st Regiment of Foot](/71st_Regiment_of_Foot), the spirited [80th Regiment of Foot (Royal Edinburgh Volunteers)](/80th_Regiment_of_Foot_(Royal_Edinburgh_Volunteers)), and the distinguished [26th (Cameronian) Regiment of Foot](/26th_(Cameronian)_Regiment_of_Foot).

Erskine's military career was a tapestry woven with the threads of major global conflicts. He distinguished himself across the [War of the Austrian Succession](/War_of_the_Austrian_Succession), where he experienced the grim realities of battle at [Fontenoy](/Battle_of_Fontenoy). The subsequent [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War) saw him rise to prominence, particularly at the [Battle of Emsdorf](/Battle_of_Emsdorf). Perhaps his most impactful service, however, came during the [American War of Independence](/American_Revolutionary_War), where he participated in pivotal engagements such as the [Battle of Long Island](/Battle_of_Long_Island), the strategic chess match at the [Battle of the Assunpink Creek](/Battle_of_the_Assunpink_Creek), the raid on [Ridgefield](/Battle_of_Ridgefield), and the brutal summer clash at [Monmouth](/Battle_of_Monmouth). As his career neared its twilight, he found himself embroiled in the [War of the First Coalition](/War_of_the_First_Coalition), facing the nascent power of revolutionary France at the [Siege of Dunkirk (1793)](/Siege_of_Dunkirk_(1793)), the fraught [Battle of Hondschoote](/Battle_of_Hondschoote), and the ill-fated [Battle of Tourcoing](/Battle_of_Tourcoing).

This impressive, if exhausting, list of engagements defines a career of relentless duty and strategic contribution. [Lieutenant-General](/Lieutenant-general_(United_Kingdom)) Sir William Erskine, 1st Baronet (1728 – 19 March 1795) was, by any measure, a seasoned [British Army](/British_Army) officer, one who served with unwavering commitment through the [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War), the [American War of Independence](/American_Revolutionary_War), and the initial, chaotic phases of the [War of the First Coalition](/War_of_the_First_Coalition). One might almost pity the man for the sheer volume of global strife he was compelled to witness and participate in.

### Background

A portrait of Erskine with his family, rendered by [David Allan](/David_Allan_(painter)), offers a rare, perhaps even jarring, glimpse into the personal life of a man whose public existence was so thoroughly dominated by military service. Erskine was born into a lineage already steeped in Scottish nobility and military tradition, being the son of Colonel the Honourable William Erskine of Torrie, who himself held the significant post of Deputy Governor of [Blackness Castle](/Blackness_Castle) in [Linlithgowshire](/Linlithgowshire). His paternal grandfather was none other than David Erskine, the second [Lord Cardross](/Lord_Cardross), linking him to a distinguished aristocratic heritage.

Sir William Erskine's personal life, like many of his era, was marked by multiple marriages. He first entered into matrimony with Magdalen Myrton, the daughter of Robert Myrton of Gogar. Following this, he married Frances Moray, a member of the prominent Moray family, daughter of James Moray of [Abercairny](/Abercairny). These unions secured his social standing and produced heirs, though the fortunes of his progeny would prove to be tragically varied.

From his second marriage to Frances, his eldest son, also named [William](/Sir_William_Erskine,_2nd_Baronet), inherited the baronetcy as the 2nd Baronet. This [William](/Sir_William_Erskine,_2nd_Baronet) pursued a military career, following in his father's formidable footsteps as a cavalry officer. However, the pressures of service, or perhaps some inherent vulnerability, led to a severe mental breakdown, culminating in his suicide in [Lisbon](/Lisbon), Portugal, in 1813. It's a stark reminder that even the most distinguished lineages are not immune to personal tragedy. Sir William had another son, [James](/Sir_James_Erskine,_3rd_Baronet), who also served as an officer, specifically in the 133rd (Fraser's) Foot. Upon the untimely death of his elder brother, [James](/Sir_James_Erskine,_3rd_Baronet) reluctantly inherited the baronetcy, becoming the 3rd Baronet. The family's unfortunate pattern continued, as Sir William's third son, John, would eventually become the baronet himself, succeeding his brother [James](/Sir_James_Erskine,_3rd_Baronet) in turn. The title, it seems, was passed through a succession of brothers, underscoring a lineage both distinguished and shadowed by misfortune.

Erskine's own military journey commenced in 1742 when he joined his father's regiment, the [7th Dragoons](/7th_Dragoons). His initial baptism by fire came during the protracted [War of the Austrian Succession](/War_of_the_Austrian_Succession), where he endured the brutal reality of combat at the [Battle of Fontenoy](/Battle_of_Fontenoy). This early exposure to large-scale warfare undoubtedly forged his resilience, preparing him for the even greater conflicts that lay ahead, particularly the global entanglement known as the [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War). By March 1759, his talents had propelled him to the rank of major, serving with distinction in Germany within the ranks of the [15th Light Dragoons](/15th_The_King%27s_Hussars). His rapid ascent continued, and by 1762, he had achieved the rank of [lieutenant-colonel](/Lieutenant-colonel), taking command of the very same regiment.

It was on the field of the [Battle of Emsdorf](/Battle_of_Emsdorf) where Erskine truly shone, performing with an exceptional degree of tactical acumen and courage. His leadership was so decisive that he was personally able to present [King George III](/George_III_of_Great_Britain) with an astonishing 16 captured [colors](/Colours,_standards_and_guidons)—battle standards seized directly from the enemy by his regiment. This feat, a tangible symbol of overwhelming victory, did not go unrewarded. For his remarkable prowess and invaluable contributions, Erskine was deservedly knighted, cementing his reputation as a formidable and highly capable officer in the eyes of the Crown.

### American War of Independence

The Erskine House in Southampton, New York, which served as Erskine's headquarters on Long Island in 1777–78, stands as a silent testament to his significant involvement in the [American War of Independence](/American_Revolutionary_War). In 1776, with the burgeoning rebellion demanding experienced leadership, Erskine was posted to America as a brigadier staff officer, serving directly under the command of [Henry Clinton](/Henry_Clinton_(American_War_of_Independence)). He was plunged immediately into the heart of the conflict, seeing extensive action in the pivotal [New York campaign](/New_York_campaign). His strategic insights and battlefield courage were quickly recognized, leading him to command the 7th Brigade during the crucial [Battle of Long Island](/Battle_of_Long_Island) on 27 August 1776, a decisive British victory that secured New York for several years.

By 1777, Erskine's strategic value was further acknowledged when he was appointed [quartermaster-general](/Quartermaster-general) to [Lord Cornwallis](/Charles_Cornwallis,_1st_Marquess_Cornwallis). It was in this capacity that Erskine is famously credited with dispensing critical advice during the events surrounding the [Battle of the Assunpink Creek](/Battle_of_the_Assunpink_Creek), also known as 'Five Mile Run.' On the night of 2 January 1777, with [George Washington's](/George_Washington) Continental Army seemingly cornered, Erskine vehemently advised Cornwallis against postponing an immediate attack. He foresaw the cunning of the "old fox" and understood the dire consequences of delay. As the story goes, Cornwallis, swayed by the ill-advised counsel of General Grant, dismissed Erskine's urgency, famously declaring, "At last we have run down the old fox… and we will bag him in the morning." Erskine, unable to contain his frustration at such shortsightedness, retorted with a prescient warning: "My Lord! If you trust those people tonight, you will see nothing of (the rebels) in the morning!" His words, unfortunately, proved prophetic. Under the cover of darkness, the Continental forces skillfully disengaged, slipping away to fight and secure a crucial victory at the [Battle of Princeton](/Battle_of_Princeton) on 3 January, a strategic blunder for the British that Erskine had clearly tried to avert. It's almost as if some people actively *choose* to ignore sound advice, isn't it?

Erskine's promotions continued, reflecting his indispensable contributions. He was made colonel of the newly formed [80th Foot](/80th_Regiment_of_Foot_(Royal_Edinburgh_Volunteers)) on 4 March 1777. Now holding the rank of [brigadier-general](/Brigadier-general), Erskine accompanied British forces as second in command under General [William Tryon](/William_Tryon), with additional support from General [James Agnew](/James_Agnew_(General)), on an audacious inland raid. Their objective: to neutralize Patriot supply depots nestled in [Danbury, Connecticut](/Danbury,_Connecticut). Following the successful destruction of these vital Patriot supplies, the British forces engaged and decisively defeated a combined force of [Continental Army](/Continental_Army) generals, including [David Wooster](/David_Wooster), [Benedict Arnold](/Benedict_Arnold) (before his infamous defection), and [Gold S. Silliman], alongside local Patriot militiamen, in the ensuing [Battle of Ridgefield](/Battle_of_Ridgefield).

His service continued through the challenging [Philadelphia campaign](/Philadelphia_campaign). After Sir William Howe's resignation in 1778, Erskine seamlessly transitioned to continue his role as [quartermaster-general](/Quartermaster-general) under the returning commander-in-chief, [Henry Clinton](/Henry_Clinton_(American_War_of_Independence)). Erskine went on to lead troops with distinction at the hard-fought [Battle of Monmouth](/Battle_of_Monmouth), a scorching summer engagement that tested the endurance of both sides. Following the conclusion of that campaign, he was entrusted with the command of the eastern district of Long Island, a strategically vital area. Erskine's final active duty assignment in North America occurred in November 1778, when he commanded a substantial force comprising five infantry battalions and a cavalry squadron. Their mission was to pursue the [Continental Army](/Continental_Army), which intelligence suggested was moving towards [Virginia](/Virginia). Having served with considerable distinction and having contributed significantly to British efforts throughout the conflict, Erskine, now promoted to [major-general](/Major-general) on 19 February 1779, sailed for London later that same year, leaving the American theatre behind. One can only imagine the sheer relief of departing a continent that had, for so long, been a crucible of conflict.

### Wars of the French Revolution

After his return from the American colonies, Erskine's career continued its upward trajectory. In 1782, he was appointed [colonel-in-chief](/Colonel-in-chief) of the esteemed [26th Foot](/26th_Foot) (Cameronians), a position of considerable prestige. His consistent service and proven capabilities were further recognized on 28 September 1787, when he received yet another promotion, achieving the formidable rank of [lieutenant-general](/Lieutenant-general). In 1791, a year before the full storm of the French Revolution was unleashed upon Europe, he was granted the hereditary title of baronet, a testament to his long and distinguished service to the Crown.

However, the peace of the late 1780s and early 1790s was not to last. With the declaration of war against revolutionary France, Erskine, despite his age, was once again called to active service. He joined the staff of [Prince Frederick, Duke of York and Albany](/Prince_Frederick,_Duke_of_York_and_Albany) in the [Flanders Campaign](/Low_Countries_theatre_of_the_War_of_the_First_Coalition), which commenced in late 1793. This campaign, marked by complex maneuvers and fierce fighting, saw Erskine present with York at the ill-fated [Siege of Dunkirk](/Siege_of_Dunkirk_(1793)), an operation that lasted from 25 August to 10 September. Following the British defeat at the [Battle of Hondschoote](/Battle_of_Hondschoote), it was Erskine who was entrusted with the critical and challenging task of commanding the retreat to [Furnes](/Veurne), a maneuver that required calm leadership under immense pressure to prevent a rout. The winter of 1793/1794 brought a temporary lull in the fighting, and during this period, Erskine was given the significant responsibility of commanding the army in York's absence, a clear indication of the trust placed in his experience and judgment.

As the spring campaign of 1794 unfolded, Erskine was once again at the forefront, given command of York's right wing in April. He demonstrated his enduring tactical prowess by successfully driving the French forces from Prémont on 16 April. However, despite this local victory, he was unfortunately unable to link up with York's main force to complete what could have been a more decisive victory at Vaux. His military contributions continued unabated. He commanded a column dispatched by Coburg to reinforce Clerfayt after a significant French breakthrough on 26 April, highlighting his role in critical defensive operations. Later, he commanded a substantial 16-squadron cavalry reserve under York's direct command at the pivotal and ultimately disastrous [Battle of Tourcoing](/Battle_of_Tourcoing) on 17–18 May, where allied forces suffered a significant defeat. His resilience was further tested as he again fought at Tournai shortly thereafter. As the campaign progressed into August, Erskine was given command of the 2nd (British) Line Corps, continuing to serve despite the increasingly grim prospects for the Allied forces in Flanders.

[Lieutenant-General](/Lieutenant-general) Sir William Erskine, 1st Baronet, finally succumbed to the inevitable on 19 March 1795, at the age of 67. He was laid to rest in [Torryburn](/Torryburn), Fife, bringing an end to a life that had been almost entirely dedicated to military service across three major global conflicts. His nickname, "Woolly" Erskine, though perhaps lacking in grandeur, speaks to a certain familiarity or perhaps a perceived temperament among his troops and peers. Whatever its origin, it's a small, human detail in a life otherwise defined by the unyielding strictures of military command.

